@NODE opti
@title "The rendering options in Landscaper"
@{b}
  You can change the following parameters in Landscaper, to affect the scene:
@{ub}

    Faults - The number of times the landscape is shifted

      Size - The number of patches long that each side of the landscape is
             Must be between 1 and 160. Larger values of size will need a
             higher resolution screen.

   X Scale - The horizontal scale of the patches

   Y Scale - The into-the-screen scale of the patches

   Z Scale - The vertical scale of the patches

     delta - The amount that any one point in the landscape can change by in
             any one fault.
@{i}
Faulting Method: This is how the program determines which points in the
                 landscape have to be raised or lowered.
@{ui}
  Circular - An imaginary circle is drawn on the landscape and any point
             within this circle is raised or lowered by a random amount up to
             the value of delta.

    Linear - An imaginary line is drawn across the landscape (between two
             points on different sides of the landscape) and any point below
             this line is raised or lowered by a random amount up to the value
             of delta.

Screen Mode- The chosen resolution for displaying the landscape. To keep the
             isometric projection looking 'correct', this table shows the
             relationship bewtween the different scales. These are all
             ratios. A z scale value of 1 always looks good.

  @{b}@{u}Example Screen@{uu}    @{u}X Scale@{uu}    @{u}Y Scale@{uu}@{ub}

   320 x 256        1         0.5
   640 x 256        1         0.25
   320 x 512        1          1
   640 x 512        1         0.5

 You can't actually put decimal values in the gadgets, so for a 320x256 you
would do x scale of 2 and y scale of 1, or bigger if you have a small size.

   Depth - The depth of the screen which will be used to draw the landscape.
             4: One colour sea
                Beach line
                Land shaded according to height
             5: Sea shaded according to depth
                Beach line
                Land shaded according to height
 To set the screenmode and depth, click on the (?) gadget. You will be
presented with a standard system requester for selecting the screenmode and
depth (either 4 or 5 = 16 or 32 colours), and you are only limited by the
screenmodes you have installed in your system.

  Defaults - Sets all parameters to their default values.

      Help - Shows a brief help window

  @{"Palette" link pale} - Brings up the palette requester window

        OK - Accepts the settings in the window and returns to the main window

    CANCEL - Rejects the settings in the window and returns to the main window

  For the best landscape use the following settings:

       Size = 160
    X scale = 2
    Y scale = 1
    Z scale = 1
Screen mode = 640 x 512 or bigger with 32 colours (depth of 5)
@ENDNODE
@NODE pale
@title "Well, colour me bad!"
@{b}
    "No that's the wrong shade." "Do the decorating yourself then bitch!"
@{ub}

    The palette requester really is a marvellous thing. Now you can create
    landscapes in any colour. Note that you must set the screenmode before
    you can use the palette editor (it'll open on the specified screen)
    but if it is smaller than 640x256, then you will need to scroll the
    screen to see all the gadgets - do this by moving the mouse to the
    edges of the screen)

    The buttons...

    Sliders - These alter the RGB components of a colour.

    Palette - You can choose which colour to alter by clicking in one of the
              coloured squares. The chosen colour will appear in the big
              square next to the sliders.

       Load - Allows you to load a standard CMAP palette like the ones saved
              with IFF's or saved in DPaint.

       Save - Allows you to save a standard CMAP palette like the ones saved
              with IFF's or saved in DPaint.

    Default - Resets all the colour values to the defaults.

     Spread - Spreads the currently selected colour to the next colour to be
              selected. To cancel, click on the current colour.

      Exch. - Exchanges the currently selected colour with the next colour
              to be selected. To cancel, click on the current colour.

       Copy - Copies the currently selected colour to the next colour to be
              selected. To cancel, click on the current colour.

         OK - Accepts the colour changes and returns to the @{"Options" link opti} window

     CANCEL - Rejects the colour changes and returns to the @{"Options" link opti} window
@ENDNODE
